Proportion of county in poor health¶

This is the response variable we will be examining in this presentation. What variables help predict poor health?

Key Questions¶

  1. Which of the x variables are the most important predictors for poor health status?
    • Which x variables does the tree-building algorithm choose to partition the most homogenous outcome groups?
  2. Are there any x variables we thought would be good predictors but are not actually?
    • For example, due to collinearity with another x variable?
  3. What interesting correlations between the predictor variables can we find?

Potential Predictor Variables¶

I think proportion of poor health might be associated with these characteristics of predictor variables available in our data set:

  • (high proportion of) uninsured
  • (low number of) primary care physicians per 1000
  • (high proportion of) adult obesity
  • (high proportion of) smokers
  • (low proportion of) high school graduation
  • (high proportion of) physical inactivity
  • (high proportion of) excessive drinking
  • (low) median household income
  • (high proportion of) severe housing problems
  • (low) life expectancy

Vizualizing what I think might be one of the stronger predictors:¶

In [12]:
sns.relplot(x='Median.Household.Income' , y='Poor.Health', data=county_data, height=4, aspect=2, hue='Food.Insecurity.Quintile', style='Income.Inequality.Quartile');

Median household income has a strong, negative, non-linear relationship with poor health.

The blue data points (lowest food insecurity) seem to be clustered at around lower poor health levels compared to other quintiles, even if they have varying median household income. Similarly, the purple data points (highest food insecurity) seem to be clustered at higher proportions of poor health. The counties with the poorest health also seem to be those in the highest income inequality quartile, represented by + markers.

I expect variables with strong correlation like proportion of smokers and life expectancy to be some of the most important variables to predict poor health.

Next, I would like to use regression lines and residual plots to check the quality of some of the weak correlations.

In [16]:
for xvar in xweaklist:
    plt.show()
    sns.residplot(x=xvar, y="Poor.Health", data=county_data)
In [17]:
for xvar in xweaklist2:
    plt.show()
    sns.residplot(x=xvar, y="Poor.Health", data=county_data)

Except for the proportion of people over 65, the residual plots all seem to exhibit extreme heteroskedasticity. This means that the residuals get larger or smaller as we are trying to make predictions for larger and larger predictive variable values. Heteroskedasticity means that the quality of correlation is not ideal.

I thus expect the number of primary care physicians per 1000, mental health providers per 1000, and population to not be good predictors of poor health.

Predictor Variable Relationships¶

We will now investigate some interesting relationships between predictor variables.

In [18]:
plot1 = sns.relplot(x='Proportion.of.Smokers', y='Excessive.Drinking', data=county_data, 
                    hue="State.Abbreviation", style="State.Abbreviation", height=10, aspect=2, 
                    markers=state_markers);

Excessive drinking is negatively correlated with proportion of smokers on the county level; I would've thought these two unhealthy activities were positively correlated with each other. For example, I was thinking that someone who is addicted to smoking might also be predisposed to have an alcohol addiction.

In [19]:
plot2 = sns.relplot(x='Percent.Rural', y='Physical.Inactivity', data=county_data, 
                    hue="State.Abbreviation", style="State.Abbreviation", height=10, aspect=2, 
                    markers=state_markers);

Percent rural is mildly positively correlated with physical inactivity; I expected that rural folk would walk more to travel. However, a reason for this positive correlation is that rural residents have to drive from place to place more, versus people who live in cities have to walk to nearby destinations or walk to public transportation.

In [20]:
plot3 = sns.relplot(x='Median.Household.Income', y='Excessive.Drinking', data=county_data, 
                    hue="State.Abbreviation", style="State.Abbreviation", height=10, aspect=2, 
                    markers=state_markers);

Excessive drinking is positively correlated with median household income but negatively correlated with poor health. Because excessive drinking is collinear with median household income, excessive drinking by itself cannot accurately predict proportion of poor health without median household income information.

A simple tree to predict proportion of poor health¶

I'll set the maximum number of leaf nodes to 10. Setting a maximum number of leaf nodes will sacrifice predictive power for increased interpretability of the model.

In [24]:
fig = plt.figure(num=None, figsize=(20, 15), dpi=80, facecolor='w', edgecolor='k')
tree.plot_tree(regtree, filled=True, feature_names=X.columns);
pass

The counties with highest proportion of poor health are the most economically disadvantaged counties.

  • The counties with the highest proportion of poor health are those that have not only a median income of less than or equal to 44,759.5 (the first node), but also less than or equal to 34,407 (the second node).

Meanwhile, the counties with the lowest proportion of poor health seem to have a relatively greater median income, have a long life expectancy, and get enough sleep.

  • The counties with the lowest proportion of poor health are those that have a median income of greater than 44,759.5 (the first node), a life expectancy of greater than 78.182 years (the second node), and have a proportion of insufficient sleep of less than 0.292.
In [25]:
train_scores = regtree.score(X_train, y_train)

print('The R-squared of this tree on the training data is ', train_scores, '.')

The R-squared of this tree on the training data is  0.7142491335488956 .
The R-squared of this tree on the test data is  0.7268349441653824 .

71.42% of the variability in poor health in the training data set is explained by the predictor variables found in the tree.

72.68% of the variability in poor health in the test data set is explained by the predictor variables found in the tree.

Because the R-squared of the training data is not significantly higher than that of the test data, this tree has not been overfit. If the tree were overfit, we would get a much more optimistic R-squared for the training data than the test data.

These importances are calculated as the Gini importance, or mean decrease in impurity of poor health in each node.

As expected, median household income is by far the most important predictor of poor health. Life expectancy is also unsurprisingly an important predictor. What surprised me the most was insufficient sleep as the third most important predictor, which now makes me wonder how important sleep is as a predictor of health for individuals rather than on the county level.

Another surprise to me was the relative lack of importance of physical inactivity and adult obesity as predictor variables. Next, we will parse whether this might be due to collinearity between these variables and the top 3 most important variables.

In [28]:
collinearity = county_data[['Median.Household.Income', 'Life.Expectancy', 'Insufficient.Sleep', 'Physical.Inactivity', 'Adult.Obesity']]
picorr=collinearity.corr()['Physical.Inactivity']
picorr.drop(labels=['Physical.Inactivity', 'Adult.Obesity'], inplace=True)
aocorr=collinearity.corr()['Adult.Obesity']
aocorr.drop(labels=['Physical.Inactivity', 'Adult.Obesity'], inplace=True)
print('collinearities for physical inactivity versus:', '\n', picorr, '\n', '\n', 'collinearities for adult obesity versus:', '\n', aocorr)

Name: Adult.Obesity, dtype: float64

There is not as much collinearity as I might have expected between median household income, life expectancy, and insufficient sleep versus physical inactivity and adult obesity. The only very collinear variables I think would be the correlation between life expectancy and physical inactivity, at r=-0.67. Maybe physical inactivity is not listed as an important variable because it is collinear with life expectancy; the information physical inactivity can provide to predict poor health is already provided by life expectancy.

The lack of collinearity between the most important variables and the other variables I thought should also be important indicate that maybe these variables simply are not as important as I thought they would be, rather than because of a collinearity issue.

Conclusions¶

  1. Which of the x variables are the most important predictors for poor health status?
  • The most important predictor is by far median household income. Other important predictors include life expectancy and insufficient sleep. Less important predictors include proportion of uninsured, smokers, and excessive drinking.
  1. Are there any x variables we thought would be good predictors but are not actually?
  • Yes; I thought adult obesity would be an important predictor of proportion of poor health, but it is actually relatively not important. Physical inactivity is also not an important predictor, but that could just be because it is too collinear with life expectancy.
  1. What interesting correlations between the predictor variables can we find?
  • Relationships I found interesting were the negative correlation between excessive drinking and proportion of smokers, the positive correlation between physical inactivity and percent rural, and the positive correlation between excessive drinking and median household income.

Suggestions for further research¶

  1. Get data for other possible predictor variables such as proportion living with families larger than 3, climate type, number of fast food restaurants per 1000, etc.
  • Are these important in predicting poor health? I'm especially interested in climate type, since I noticed many of the lower proportion of poor health counties were located in the northern US.
  1. Get this data from 100 years ago.
  • Has the importance of predictors changed over time?
  1. Research successful initiatives to decrease proportion of poor health.
  • This would probably entail less statistical analysis and reading more case studies.
  1. Research why exactly median household income is the most important predictor of poor health.
  • What do counties with higher median income do differently to keep their residents healthy? Variation in proportion of poor health in counties with low median household income can also be explored.
